\layout Subsection

Magnetosphere
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Magnetosphere}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We adopt the magnetospherical accretion flow model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

, as done so by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

 and by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

, in which the gas accretion on to the stellar surface from the innermost
 part of the accretion disc occurs through a dipolar stellar magnetic field.
 The magnetic field is assumed to be so strong that the gas flow does not
 affect the underlying magnetic field itself.
 As shown in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

, the innermost radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

) of the magnetophere at the equatorial plane (
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset 

) is assigned to be same as the inner radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{di}}$
\end_inset 

) of the accretion disc where the flow is truncated.
 In our models, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 and the outer radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

) of the magnetosphere (at the equaotrial plane) are set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2.2\, R_{\sun}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3.0\, R_{\sun}$
\end_inset 

 respectively.
 The former value corresponds to the corotation radius of the accretion
 disc, and the geometry of the magnetic field/stream lines is kept constant
 throghout this paper.
 The geometry of the magnetosphere is identical to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

small/wide
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{muzerolle:2001}
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The magnetic field and the gas stream lines are assumed to have the following
 simple form: 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R_{\mathrm{m}}\sin^{2}\theta$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep[see][]{ghosh:1977}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 are coordinates of the field point (
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

) in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

 in spheical coodinates, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset 

is the radial distance to the field line at the equotorial plane (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/2$
\end_inset 

).
 The range of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset 

is restricted between 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

 as mentioned above.
 Using the field geometry above, the conservation of energy, and igoring
 the rotation of magnetosphere, the velocity and the density of the accreting
 gas along the steam line can be found.
 See 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

 for details.
 
\layout Standard

In all of our models, the temperature structure of the magnetospheric used
 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

 is also adoped here.
 The temperature structure was computed assuming a volumetric heating rate
 which is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-3}$
\end_inset 

, and using the energy balance of the radiative cooling rate of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Open

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1982}
\end_inset 

 and the heating rate 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

.
 Although the temperature structure of the accretion steam could significantly
 affect the line source function, for the purpose of the expolaring the
 general characteristics of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 formation, this simple form is a reasonable assumption.
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{martin:1996}
\end_inset 

 presented the self-consistent determination of the thermal structure of
 the inflowing gas along the dipole magnetic field, same as the one used
 here, by solving the heat equation couple to trate equations for hydrogen.
 He found that main heat source is adiabatic compression due to the convering
 nature of the flow, and the major contirbutors of the cooling process are
 bremsstrahling radiation and line emission from Ca\SpecialChar ~
II and Mg\SpecialChar ~
II ions.
 The temerature sturcture of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{martin:1996}
\end_inset 

 qualitaively agrees with that of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

.
 The sensitivty tests of H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 on the temperature structure will be presented later (SPECIFY THE SECTION
 LATER).
 
\layout Standard

As the infalling gas becomes closer to the stellar surface, it is decelerates
 in a strong shock, and heated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{6}\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 (with typical parameters).
 The X-ray radiation produced in the shock will be absorbed by the gas located
 near, and reemitted in optical and UV radiation (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:1991}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

).
 This will create hot rings near the stellar surface where the magnetic
 field intersects with the surface.
 For simplicity, the free-falling kinetic energy is assumed to be thermalized
 in the radiating layer, and reemits as blackbody radiation (with a single
 temerature).
 With the parameters of the magnetosphere and the star given above (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

), about 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
per\SpecialChar ~
cent of the surface is covered by the hot rings, and its temperature
 is about 
\begin_inset Formula $6400\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

.
 If the mass-accretion rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-7}\,\mathrm{M_{\sun}\, yr^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

, the ratio of this accretion luminosity to the photospheric luminosity
 is about 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset 

.
 The contiuum emission from the hot rings is taken into account when computing
 the line profiles.
 
\layout Subsection

Colliminated Wind
\layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:wind_jet}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

As mentioned earlier, the wind model presented here is to simulate the collimina
ted MHD disc-wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in large scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) , and the alternative wind model which resembles the model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 in small scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU) will be presented larter (section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Alternative-model-disc-wind}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

Based on the simple model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

, the following parametrisation of colliminated wind/jet (region 3 in Fig.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_dipolar}

\end_inset 

) is adopeted.
 The wind velocity field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{\mathrm{wind}}\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset 

, is consist of radial and polar components which depend only on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 respectively.
 The radial componet 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset 

 is assumed to be in the classical beta-velocity law 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citep[c.f.][]{castor:1979}
\end_inset 

, and the azimuthal component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}$
\end_inset 

 is asuumed to be a constant fraction (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

) of the Keplerian velocity for a given distance (
\begin_inset Formula $w=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}$
\end_inset 

) from the symmetry axis (
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

-axis) , i.e.:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\mathbf{v}_{\mathrm{wind}} & = & v_{r}\hat{\mathbf{r}}+v_{\phi}\hat{\mathbf{\bphi}}+v_{\theta}\hat{\btheta}\label{eq:wind_velocity_def}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{r}\left(r\right)=v_{r0}+\left(v_{\infty}-v_{r0}\right)\left(1-\frac{R_{\mathrm{mo}}}{r}\right)^{\beta}\,,\label{eq:wind_velocity_radial_part}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{\phi}\left(w\right)=\gamma\,\left(\frac{GM_{*}}{w}\right)^{1/2}\,,\label{eq:wind_velocity_azimuth_part}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{\theta}\left(r,\theta\right)=v_{\theta0}\,\left(\frac{R_{\mathrm{mo}}}{r}\right)^{\alpha}\frac{\tan\theta}{\left|\tan\theta\right|}\,.\label{eq:wind_velocity_polar_part}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Note that the base of the wind starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

, and the range of the polar angle is restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>\left|\theta_{\mathrm{disc}}\right|$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{disc}}$
\end_inset 

 is the openning angle of the accretion disc, to avoid the overlap.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r0}$
\end_inset 

is the small radial velocity at the base of the wind (
\begin_inset Formula $r=R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

).
 Normally, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r0}=10\,\mathrm{km\, s^{-1}}$
\end_inset 

, approximately the thermal velocity of hydrogen with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=7500\,\mathrm{K}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.05$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{appenzeller:2005}
\end_inset 

) are used.
 The dependency of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset 

 in polar direction (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset 

) on the values of wind accerelation parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 is shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

.
 All other parameters describing the wind are fixed as the standard values
 given in Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Further, the density of the wind is assumed to be axi-symmetric and separable
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset 

 for computationaly simpliciy, i.e., 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho\left(r,\theta\right)=P\left(r\right)\, F\left(\theta\right)\label{eq:wind_density_def}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F\left(\theta\right)=n\,\cos^{b}\theta\label{eq:wind_density_theta}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 is normally positive even number (for the density symmetric about the equtotria
l plane), and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 is the angular normalisation constant.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset 

, the wind is sherically symmetic exept for the parts dirupted by the accretion
 disc.
 The larger the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

, the higher the degree of the collimination.
 By integrating equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:wind_density_theta}

\end_inset 

 over angles and normalising the integral to 
\begin_inset Formula $4\pi$
\end_inset 

, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
n=\frac{1+b}{1-\cos^{1+b}\theta_{\mathrm{wind}}}\,.\label{eq:wind_density_theta_norm}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Asumming the total mass-loss rate by the wind/jet is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}$
\end_inset 

 and the mass-flux conserves in time, the radial part of the density function
 is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(r\right)=\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}\,\left[4\pi r^{2}v_{r}\left(r\right)\right]^{-1}$
\end_inset 

; hence, Equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:wind_density_def}

\end_inset 

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho\left(r,\theta\right)=\frac{n\,\cos^{b}\theta\,\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}}{4\pi r^{2}\, v_{r}\left(r\right)}\,.\label{eq:wind_density_final}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 For a given mass-accretion rate, the wind mass-loss rate in our typical
 model is assined from the ratio of mass-loss to mass-accretion rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{wind}}/\dot{M}_{\mathrm{acc}}\approx0.1$
\end_inset 

), indicated by both observations and magnetohydrodynamical calculations
 (see e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{koenigl:2000}
\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:wind_vr_rho}

\end_inset 

 shows the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

 in polar direction (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset 

) for different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 with all other parameters fixed as the standard values (Table\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:std_parameters}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard


