AU).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 

 introduced the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

split-monople
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 kinematic disc-wind model in their studies of the UV resonance lines formed
 in the winds of cataclysmic variable stars.
 In this model, the outflow arises from the surface of the rotating accretion
 disc, and has a biconical geometry.
 The specfic angular momentum is assumed to be conserved along a stream
 line, and the poloidal velocity component is assumed to be simply a radial
 from vertically displaced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

soruces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 from the central star.
 We adopt their disc-wind model here, and consider the combined effect of
 the disc-wind and the magnetospherical accretion flow model described earlier.
 In the following, we breifely described their disc-wind model.
 For details of the models, readers are refered to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{knigge:1995}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{long:2002}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Four basic parameters for the models are: 1.
 mass-loss rate, 2.\SpecialChar ~
the degree of the wind collimination, 3.\SpecialChar ~
velocity gradients,
 and 4.\SpecialChar ~
the wind temperature.
 The basic configuration of the disc-wind model is shown in Figure\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:config_discwind}

\end_inset 

.
 The disc wind originates from the disc surface, but the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 point (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset 

), from which the stream lines diverges, are placed at distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

 above and below the centre of the star.
 By changing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, the degree of the wind collimination is controled.
 The larger the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, the wind becomes more parallel to the rotation axis, i.e.
 the wind becomes more colliminated.
 The mass-loss lanching is restricted between 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wi}}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wo}}$
\end_inset 

 where the former is set to be equal to the outer radius of the magnetosphere
 (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{mo}}$
\end_inset 

) for similicity and the latter is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset 

\SpecialChar ~
AU as in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The local mass-loss rate per unit area (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{m}$
\end_inset 

) is assumed to be proportional to the mid-plane temperature of the disc,
 and is a function of the cylindical radius 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\left(x^{2}+y^{2}\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset 

 , i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{m}\left(w\right)\propto T\left(w\right)^{\alpha}\,\,.\label{eq:discwind-massloss-temp}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Futher, the mid-plane tempetrature of the disc is assumed to be expressed
 as a power-law in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset 

; thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $T\propto w^{q}$
\end_inset 

.
 Using this in the relation above, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\dot{m}\left(w\right)\propto w^{p}\label{eq:discwind-massloss-w}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\alpha\times q$
\end_inset 

.
 The index of the mid-plane temperature power law is adopted from the dust
 radiative transfer model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{whitney:2003a}
\end_inset 

 who found the inner most part of the accretion disc has 
\begin_inset Formula $q=-1.15$
\end_inset 

.
 To be consistent with the colliminated disc-wind model of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{krasnopolsky:2003}
\end_inset 

 who used 
\begin_inset Formula $p=-3/2$
\end_inset 

, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is set to 1.3.
 The constant of proportionality in equation\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:discwind-massloss-w}

\end_inset 

 is found by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{m}$
\end_inset 

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wi}}$
\end_inset 

to 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathrm{wo}}$
\end_inset 

, and the normalizing the total mass-loss rate to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{M}_{\mathrm{dw}}$
\end_inset 

.
 (CHECK THE VALUE OF ALPHA AGAIN!)
\layout Standard

The azimutal/rotational component of the wind velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}\left(w,z\right)$
\end_inset 

 is computed from the Keplerian rotational velocity at the emerging point
 of the stream line i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}\left(w_{i},0\right)=\left(GM_{*}/w_{i}\right)^{1/2}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset 

 is the distance from the rotational axis (
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

) to the emerging point on the disc, and by assuming the conservation of
 the specific angular momentum along a stream line: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{\phi}\left(w,z\right)\,=v_{\phi}\left(w_{i},0\right)\,\left(\frac{w_{i}}{w}\right)\label{eq:discwind-toroidal-velocity}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

.
 Based on the classic 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset 

 velocity law of hot steller winds (c.f.\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{castor:1975}
\end_inset 

), the poloidal component of the wind velocity (
\begin_inset Formula $v_{p}$
\end_inset 

) parameterized as: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
v_{p}\left(w_{i},l\right)=c_{\mathrm{s}}\left(w_{i}\right)+\left[f\, v_{\mathrm{esc}}-c_{\mathrm{s}}\left(w_{i}\right)\right]\left(1-\frac{R_{s}}{l+R_{s}}\right)^{\beta}\label{eq:discwind-poloidal-velocity}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\mathrm{s}}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 are the sound speed at the wind lanching point on the disc, the constant
 scale factor of the asymptotic terminal velocity to the local escape velocity
 (from the wind emerging point on the disc), and the distance from the disc
 surface along stream lines respecively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{s}$
\end_inset 

 is the wind scale length, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{s}=10\, R_{\mathrm{mi}}$
\end_inset 

 is adopted as similarly done by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{long:2002}
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Assuming the mass-flux conservation and using the velocity field defined
 above, the disc wind density as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 can be written as
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho\left(w_{i},l\right)=\frac{\dot{m}\left(w_{i}\right)}{v_{p}\left(w_{i},l\right)\,\left|\cos\delta\right|}\,\left\{ \frac{d}{Q\left(w_{i},l\right)\,\cos\delta}\right\} ^{2}\label{eq:discwind-density}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset 

 are the distance from the source point (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset 

) to a point along the stream line and the angle between the stream line
 and the disc normal respectively.
\layout Standard

