 colliminated wind, and the accreation disc.
 Previously in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{symington:2005}
\end_inset 

, the model used in the three-dimentional (3-D) adaptive mesh refinement
 (AMR) to inverstigate the line variability mainly associated with roational
 motion of complex geometrical configurations of magnetospherical flow (see
 also 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt*{kurosawa:2005a}
\end_inset 

).
 We modefied the code to handle the two-dimentional (2-D) density distribution,
 and restricted our models to be axi-symmetric.
 It was done so in order to enable us to explore rather large number of
 parameter spaces (c.f.\SpecialChar ~
section\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:model-configuration}

\end_inset 

).
 Note that the velocity field is still in 3-D -- the third component can
 be calculated by using the symmetry for a given value of azimutal angle.
