 is constructed are presented in e.g.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{wolf:1999}
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{kurosawa:2001a}
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{steinacker:2003} 
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The computation of the H
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 is devided in two parts: 1.\SpecialChar ~
the source function calculation (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\nu}$
\end_inset 

) and 2.\SpecialChar ~
the observed flux/profile calulcation.
 In the first process, we have utilized the method by 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{klein:1978}
\end_inset 

 (see also 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citealt{rybicki:1978}
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{hartmann:1994}
\end_inset 

) in which the Sobolev approximation method is applied.
 The population of the bound states of hydrogen are assumed to be in statistical
 equilibrium, and the gas to be in radiative equilibrium.
 Our hydrogen atom model consist of 14 bound state and continuum.
 Readers are refer to 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
citet{klein:1978}
\end_inset 

 for details.
 (AND MORE..)
